Use double quotes for normal text:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    greeting = "Hello"
]

Expression-position backtick strings aren't implemented. Use an ordinary string
with escapes when the text contains backslashes:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    windows_path = "C:\\docs\\site"
]

Use single quotes for one character:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    seedling = '🌱'
]

Use a template when text needs values or a larger structure:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    name = "Priya"

    greeting = [:
        Hello, [name]
    ]
]

### Joining strings

Use templates to join strings together. Put the parts inside square brackets:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    first = "Hello, "
    second = "world"
    message = [first, second]
]

Don't use `+` to join strings. `+` is for numbers only:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    -- WRONG: this won't compile
    -- message = first + second
]

### Strings are read-only

A quoted string like `"Hello"` is read-only content. You can reassign a
mutable binding to point at a different string, but you can't change the
string itself.

Square brackets belong to templates. Collections use curly braces instead.
